StringWithMarkup.String: 1-Hydroxyanthraquinone's former production and use as a dye may have resulted in its release to the environment through various waste streams. If released to air, a vapor pressure of 2.09X10-7 mm Hg at 25 °C indicates 1-hydroxyanthraquinone will exist in both the vapor and particulate phases in the ambient atmosphere. Vapor-phase 1-hydroxyanthraquinone will be degraded in the atmosphere by reaction with photochemically-produced hydroxyl radicals; the half-life for this reaction in air is estimated to be 28 hrs. Particulate-phase 1-hydroxyanthraquinone will be removed from the atmosphere by wet and dry deposition. 1-Hydroxyanthraquinone isomers photodecompose under irradiation with visible light in aerated alkaline solution, with phthalic acid as the main product. If released to soil, 1-hydroxyanthraquinone is expected to have slight mobility based upon an estimated Koc of 2,000. Volatilization from moist soil surfaces is not expected to be an important fate process based upon an estimated Henry's Law constant of 7.2X10-9 atm-cu m/mole. Biodegradation is not expected to be an important environmental fate process based on a 1-5% theoretical BOD using activated sludge and the Japanese MITI test. However, in most anoxic sediments, uncharged simple anthraquinone dyes exhibit half-lives of less than 10 days. If released into water, 1-hydroxyanthraquinone is expected to adsorb to suspended solids and sediment based upon the estimated Koc. Section.Description: Sorption to soils and sediments is an important factor on the transport and fate of organic contaminants in the environment.  The soil/water adsorption coefficient, also known as solid-water distribution coefficient (Kd), measures the amount of chemical substance adsorbed onto soil per amount of water.  Since adsorption occurs predominantly by partition into the soil organic matter, it is more useful to normalize the Kd value to the organic carbon content of a soil and express the distribution coefficient in Koc (organic carbon normalized distribution coefficient).  The greater the Kd (or Koc) value, the less likely a chemical will leach or contribute to runoff.  A very high value means it is strongly adsorbed onto soil and organic matter and does not move throughout the soil.
